Such is the evidence of those writers, Greek or Roman, who deal with the local habitation of the Cimbri rather than with the general history of that tribe. As a measure of the inde- finitude of their ideas, we have the confusion, already noticed, between the Cimbri and Cimmerii, on the parts of Diodorus, Strabo and Plutarch. A better measure occurs in the follow· ing extract from Pliny, who not only fixes the Cimbri in three places at once, hut also (as far as we can find any meaning in his language) removes them so far northward as Norway: “Alterum genus lugaevones3 quorum pars Cimbri, Teutoni, ac Chaucorum gentes.
